recordings.rmk: Nocturnal recording in the city, high pass filter 4000 Hz 6 dB, ZOOM H1n.

Calls from a group of freshly arrived migrant Redwings that were roosting (in daytime) among sapling trees and shrubs. As well as the typical 'seeee' note, the equally diagnostic hard 'jack' can he heard [at 0:05; 0:06; 0:14; 0:15; 0:17; 0:19 and 0:23].

A group of migrant Redwings shared the shelter offered by a group of Sycamore trees with at least one Blackbird. I left my recorder among the tree foliage in close proximity to the birds. As well as the typical high-pitched and penetrating 'zeep' call of Redwing [three times over the first eight seconds, then really clear at 0:10; next, much quieter, at 0:13 and, quite clear, at 0:17 - close to the eighteenth second] the more Blackbird-like, chacking alarm call (of Redwing) can also be heard [0:09; 0:17; 0:30]. Of more interest is the comparison between the Redwing's 'jack' and the equivalent call from Blackbird. To me, the Redwing's call is more emphatic and indignant (it sounds as though the bird has just sat on a pin) and the Blackbird's note is lower, more muffled and less panicky.  Examples of Blackbird 'chucks' are at 0:01; 0:05; 0:08 and 0:15. A nice comparison of the two species can be heard between the seventh and ninth seconds: Blackbird at just before the eighth second, followed by Redwing. Another sequence that provides a great comparison is from the 26th second to the end of the clip, about nine seconds later. The first two calls are from Blackbird, the next is Redwing, the last three are Blackbird.
